<span id="freeTextContainer15109097732922025647">DNF at around page 71. <br/>Oh God. Where to begin.<br/>The first ten pages or so were okay, but it rapidly started going downhill from there. The writing was bland, average, and lacking. The characters were so generic and two-dimensional, like mere illusions of what teenagers actually act like. The sixteen-year-old protagonists sounded like TEN YEAR OLDS, as did all of the other children, whose ages in the book ranged from about 12 or so to 18. The parents were equally stupid. Last but not least, the plo</span>
  <span id="freeText15109097732922025647" style="display:none">DNF at around page 71. <br />Oh God. Where to begin.<br />The first ten pages or so were okay, but it rapidly started going downhill from there. The writing was bland, average, and lacking. The characters were so generic and two-dimensional, like mere illusions of what teenagers actually act like. The sixteen-year-old protagonists sounded like TEN YEAR OLDS, as did all of the other children, whose ages in the book ranged from about 12 or so to 18. The parents were equally stupid. Last but not least, the plot...Here we have a few kids who go on vacation/to an unknown place, only to be swept off into a magical kingdom...<br />ITS BEEN DONE BEFORE.<br />HUNDREDS. OF. TIMES. <br /><br />By about page 40, I wanted to throw this book across the room. By page 50, I wanted to rip it to shreds. By about 70, I thought, “I CAN’T TAKE THIS ANYMORE!” Thank goodness that this was a libray book. I want nothing to do with Mere Enchantment ever again.</span>
